President Obama met with Ambassador Princeton Lyman, his Special Envoy for Sudan, to discuss the political and humanitarian crisis in Abyei and the violence in Southern Kordofan. The President expressed concern over the violence and lack of humanitarian access and emphasized the need for cooperative negotiations to implement the 2005 Comprehensive Peace Agreement. Ambassador Lyman updated the President on Secretary of State Clinton's meetings with the parties involved. President Obama gave his full support to Ambassador Lyman's work and acknowledged the contributions of Ethiopian Prime Minister Meles Zenawi and African Union Panel leader Thabo Mbeki towards peace. Ambassador Lyman plans to return to the region to help translate political agreements into security arrangements. The President urged Sudan's leaders not to waste the opportunity for peace and prosperity.